06017nam a22007575i 9781554583126DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132011xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815545831267 a10.51644/97815545831262doi  a(DE-B1597)667292  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aSOC0150002bisacsh04a304.222200aEcologies of Affect :bPlacing Nostalgia, Desire, and Hope /ced. by Ondine Park, Tonya K. Davidson, Rob Shields. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2013] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b37 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEnvironmental Humanities00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tIntroduction -- tNostalgia -- t“Not everything was good, but many things were better” -- tNostalgia and Postmemories of a Lost Place -- tPlacing Nostalgia -- tFrom Disease to Desire -- tDesire -- tThe Tourist Affect -- t(In)Human Desiring and Extended Agency -- tCityscapes of Desire -- tIllustrating Desires -- tHope -- tThe Virtual Places of Childhood -- tVirtual Resurrections -- tPerforming Spaces of Hope -- tThe Spatial Distribution of Hope In and Beyond Fort McMurray -- tSpectacular Enclosures of Hope -- tA Roundtable on the Affective Turn -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tEnvironmental Humanities Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEcologies of Affect offers a synthetic introduction to the felt dynamics of cities and the character of places. The contributors capture the significance of affects including desire, nostalgia, memory, and hope in forming the identity and tone of places. The critical intervention this collection of essays makes is an active, consistent engagement with the virtualities that produce and refract our idealized attachments to place. Contributors show how place images, and attempts to build communities, are, rather than abstractions, fundamentally tied to and revolve around such intangibles. We understand nostalgia, desire, and hope as virtual; that is, even though they are not material, they are nevertheless real and must be accounted for. In this book, the authors take up affect, emotion, and emplacement and consider them in relation to one another and how they work to produce and are produced by certain temporal and spatial dimensions. The aim of the book is to inspire readers to consider space and place beyond their material properties and attend to the imaginary places and ideals that underpin and produce material places and social spaces. This collection will be useful to practitioners and students seeking to understand the power of affect and the importance of virtualities within contemporary societies, where intangible goods have taken on an increasing value.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural geography. 0aGeographical perception. 0aSocial ecology. 4aCultural Studies. 4aSocial Science: Urban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh1 aBuffam, Bonar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCambre, Maria-Carolina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Tonya K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Tonya K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDogu, Goze, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDora, Veronica Della, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorow, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHroch, Petra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHui, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJac